WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:05.640
 So now we're going to do a real, simple run-through of the kinds of things that you can do in HTML and forms.

00:00:05.640 --> 00:00:13.120
 This is only the beginning and there's so many great online resources for how to do forms in HTML.

00:00:13.120 --> 00:00:17.880
 So I've already showed you the basic text field, we'll talk about the password field, radio button,

00:00:17.880 --> 00:00:25.280
 checkbox, select and drop-down, and I just got kind of this one HTML page that you can view the source of and borrow.

00:00:25.280 --> 00:00:29.120
 I kind of write this stuff up for me for a quick reference.

00:00:29.120 --> 00:00:34.160
 So we've already talked about the text field, right?

00:00:34.160 --> 00:00:39.160
 So input type equals text and then the name is the value.

00:00:39.160 --> 00:00:41.360
 The ID, don't get too stuck on the ID.

00:00:41.360 --> 00:00:50.440
 The ID has to do with how you associate the label tag with the field and so that that knows that somehow account and this text box are connected.

00:00:50.440 --> 00:00:57.160
 So the ID is more of a browser thing and the name equals is the thing that's going to be sent to the browser.

00:00:57.160 --> 00:01:03.040
 So the browser is always going to get key value pairs and so, you know, when we type Beth and we hit submit,

00:01:03.040 --> 00:01:07.720
 then we're going to get the incoming post data is going to have the value account equals Beth.

00:01:07.720 --> 00:01:18.000
 Now, if you look at password, that's a type, password for all intents and purposes is a text type and it shows it so people can't shoulder surf and see what it is.

00:01:18.000 --> 00:01:23.840
 Of course, they can watch you type your password, but it shows asterisks in the box while you're typing.

00:01:23.840 --> 00:01:35.080
 But then it's important to realize that once the data is submitted, the data is submitted in plain text and until here's another one, another nickname.

00:01:35.080 --> 00:01:38.240
 So Nick equals and I see Kate.

00:01:38.240 --> 00:01:42.880
 So that's that's basically the variance of the input types of text.

00:01:42.880 --> 00:01:47.400
 Hidden type equals hidden is another one where you just don't see it in the user interface.

00:01:47.400 --> 00:01:51.040
 We're going to use one of those input type equals in a bit.

00:01:51.040 --> 00:01:56.640
 A radio button is designed for situations where there you can only pick one of two things.

00:01:56.640 --> 00:01:58.560
 So when you hit AM, the PM goes off.

00:01:58.560 --> 00:02:03.480
 When you hit PM, the AM goes off and you can actually have a whole bunch of them and you can click them.

00:02:03.480 --> 00:02:08.800
 Now, now they're they're drawn together because they're type equals radio and then the name is identical.

00:02:08.800 --> 00:02:12.000
 And interestingly, you can scatter these literally all over the page.

00:02:12.000 --> 00:02:15.920
 It doesn't lead to very good user interface, but the way you go.

00:02:15.920 --> 00:02:25.480
 And so what happens is, is again, no matter how many of these you put with a name equals when, no matter where you put them on the page, if you click one, all the others are going to turn off.

00:02:25.480 --> 00:02:28.640
 And so the one that's clicked, they all have different values.

00:02:28.640 --> 00:02:39.600
 And so what will happen is whatever one is clicked at the moment that you actually send it, that will be the key value pair where when equals PM because only one can be selected.

00:02:39.600 --> 00:02:43.520
 And it's up to you to make these things unique or you don't maybe don't want to be unique.

00:02:43.520 --> 00:02:45.600
 You do whatever you want.

00:02:45.600 --> 00:02:48.440
 And so in this case, the PM one is selected.

00:02:48.440 --> 00:02:52.640
 So we see when equals PM in the incoming post data.

00:02:52.640 --> 00:02:55.000
 So that's a radio button.

00:02:55.000 --> 00:02:57.040
 So this is a checkbox.

00:02:57.040 --> 00:03:01.760
 This is more probably more useful in many ways.

00:03:01.760 --> 00:03:06.360
 Checkboxes, you can have as many that you want and each of them are individual and distinct.

00:03:06.360 --> 00:03:14.440
 So if you take a look, for example, you see that you have different names to class one, class two and class three.

00:03:14.440 --> 00:03:22.480
 So that each checkbox has its own name, but the checkboxes are actually just little checkboxes.

00:03:22.480 --> 00:03:23.880
 The text here is just text.

00:03:23.880 --> 00:03:26.480
 The text is not really a critical part of it.

00:03:26.480 --> 00:03:31.840
 The value is what will get sent if that checkbox is checked.

00:03:31.840 --> 00:03:36.680
 And so in this example, we've checked pie free and SI 539.

00:03:36.680 --> 00:03:42.560
 And you'll notice that two of them have values and one of them doesn't.

00:03:42.560 --> 00:03:45.760
 Now, the key is often you're just checking to see if the data is there.

00:03:45.760 --> 00:03:51.480
 In this case, class three is not in the post data and class one is on.

00:03:51.480 --> 00:03:52.400
 That's the default.

00:03:52.400 --> 00:03:59.040
 If you don't say value equals, it's like value equals on or whatever the value is that you put in that checkbox.

00:03:59.040 --> 00:04:01.120
 And so you get to decide these.

00:04:01.120 --> 00:04:10.640
 You might easily think that you don't need any values whatsoever because you're really looking for the name of the field and you want the name of the field to be distinct.

00:04:10.640 --> 00:04:13.560
 And so again, you can check as many of the checkboxes as you want.

00:04:13.560 --> 00:04:14.280
 You can uncheck them.

00:04:14.280 --> 00:04:17.320
 You can check none of them and you can check all of them.

00:04:17.320 --> 00:04:18.600
 So those are checkboxes.

00:04:18.600 --> 00:04:27.600
 So to describe a drop down, a drop down is a multiple choice option basically for a single value that's going to be sent back to you.

00:04:27.600 --> 00:04:36.520
 And so we have a select, which is the whole thing, and that gives the name the key, the keyword that is going to be sent back to.

00:04:36.520 --> 00:04:38.360
 And then we have a series of options.

00:04:38.360 --> 00:04:42.320
 And you'll notice there's no value on the select, but each option has its own value.

00:04:42.320 --> 00:04:45.720
 Right. So I happen to be going zero, one, two, and these are strings, not numbers.

00:04:45.720 --> 00:04:49.280
 They often are just numbers to make our lives simple.

00:04:49.280 --> 00:04:52.680
 And then you have some text, et cetera, et cetera, et cetera.

00:04:52.680 --> 00:04:53.760
 And so you pick one.

00:04:53.760 --> 00:04:56.640
 In this case, I leave it default and I hit the submit.

00:04:56.640 --> 00:04:59.080
 So soda is going to be equal to zero.

00:04:59.080 --> 00:05:02.960
 So this happened to be the one that selected when we hit submit.

00:05:02.960 --> 00:05:05.560
 OK, so that's what a select looks like.

00:05:05.560 --> 00:05:10.200
 You can also make a select that has some defaulted one.

00:05:10.200 --> 00:05:12.680
 And so you just put selected on one of them.

00:05:12.680 --> 00:05:14.520
 So that means it's the drop down.

00:05:14.520 --> 00:05:15.680
 They're all there, right?

00:05:15.680 --> 00:05:16.120
 They're all there.

00:05:16.120 --> 00:05:23.000
 If you click on this thing, you'll see if you click on which snack you're going to see all the different snacks, peanuts is preselected.

00:05:23.000 --> 00:05:29.760
 And if I don't change it and hit submit, then we're going to see snack equals the value, which is peanuts.

00:05:29.760 --> 00:05:34.360
 So that's an example that you don't have to make numbers, although it's really common to be using numbers.

00:05:34.360 --> 00:05:38.280
 So that's a drop down with a default other than the first item.

00:05:38.280 --> 00:05:42.520
 The default is it's the first item unless you do it otherwise.

00:05:42.520 --> 00:05:48.920
 When you're typing in comments or a blog post, big long blob of text, you use a text area tag.

00:05:48.920 --> 00:05:52.600
 The text area tag is a little bit different in that it doesn't have a value equals.

00:05:52.600 --> 00:05:56.000
 It does have a name equals.

00:05:56.000 --> 00:06:00.520
 It has rows and columns to tell how tall it is and how wide it is.

00:06:00.520 --> 00:06:05.280
 There are clever styling libraries that make these a little prettier.

00:06:05.280 --> 00:06:10.840
 But basically what it is, it's a series of text, including paragraphs, including new lines, et cetera.

00:06:10.840 --> 00:06:16.200
 And you're just allowed to type with new lines and edit and cursor around in here and build all kind of stuff.

00:06:16.200 --> 00:06:20.280
 And then you send it in and you can put default text in here.

00:06:20.280 --> 00:06:21.280
 You can edit the text.

00:06:21.280 --> 00:06:22.400
 You can change it.

00:06:22.400 --> 00:06:28.440
 And it comes in as a key value pair with new lines and everything and any weird spacing that you might put in.

00:06:28.440 --> 00:06:38.960
 But it's basically a block of text like a comment or like a like a comment or a blog post or something like that.

00:06:38.960 --> 00:06:43.320
 So the last thing on this page here is the submit button.

00:06:43.320 --> 00:06:48.240
 And so you can make a type equals submit and you can give it a name.

00:06:48.240 --> 00:06:51.520
 And again, that's a key value pair and a value.

00:06:51.520 --> 00:06:58.040
 Now, the submit is a little bit weird in that the value actually appears on the submit.

00:06:58.040 --> 00:07:06.560
 But what we tend to do is this submit and if you were in a multi-language environment, you're going to want that to be whatever language of the user.

00:07:06.560 --> 00:07:15.000
 So usually what we do is we I name, carefully name the variables or the name of the form.

00:07:15.000 --> 00:07:17.040
 And then I check for this to exist.

00:07:17.040 --> 00:07:27.040
 And if I have a bunch of buttons, I name them differently and don't really actually look at this text because that text might want to be translated at some point in time.

00:07:27.040 --> 00:07:29.040
 So that's an input type.

00:07:29.040 --> 00:07:30.840
 Input type equals button.

00:07:30.840 --> 00:07:38.240
 This is a little pattern where I'm going to do like an escape or a back or something like that.

00:07:38.240 --> 00:07:44.760
 And then sometimes it's easier just to do some little JavaScript and what this little JavaScript chunk is.

00:07:44.760 --> 00:07:51.600
 Location.href equals quote www.djfree.com return false.

00:07:51.600 --> 00:08:05.280
 What this says is it actually sort of when you press this escape button, it goes up in the browser and in effect pastes this little URL into the URL bar and then hits enter and return false keeps the form from being submitted.

00:08:05.280 --> 00:08:12.320
 And so this is a way that I often will put a simple cancel or escape or something else in a form.

00:08:12.320 --> 00:08:20.920
 Just if I know the URL I want to go back to or go to, then you can put it in here and on click location.href.

00:08:20.920 --> 00:08:27.680
 So those are the input types that have been around for probably 20 years.

00:08:27.680 --> 00:08:30.400
 Yeah, at least 20, 25 years.

00:08:30.400 --> 00:08:39.240
 HTML5 is a more recent phenomenon, although by now it's pretty well supported in most browsers, to find a whole new set of input types.

00:08:39.240 --> 00:08:49.040
 And what's nice about this is we were slowly but surely building complex libraries to solve all these problems, but now we can use these input types and now each browser can support them to their own way.

00:08:49.040 --> 00:08:52.240
 And they all fall back to type equals text.

00:08:52.240 --> 00:08:56.360
 And so if you have a really old browser, these don't cause trouble.

00:08:56.360 --> 00:09:00.120
 So here's just some samples of some things.

00:09:00.120 --> 00:09:06.760
 So type equals color is a color picker and that's going to pop up a color picker, let you cruise around.

00:09:06.760 --> 00:09:12.600
 That color picker is defined by the browser and usually the operating system and so you'll pick a color.

00:09:12.600 --> 00:09:23.920
 And that color is going to go in in hex format and that's the red, the green and the blue and so that's what colors look like.

00:09:23.920 --> 00:09:36.760
 You can have type equals date and so here's a date and they pop in here, you're going to pop up a date picker for the birthday, you'll pop up a date picker and you'll be able to kind of move around and pick a date and then that'll put that date in as a string.

00:09:36.760 --> 00:09:41.280
 They're all going to turn into strings when they're being sent in.

00:09:41.280 --> 00:09:51.040
 There's a couple of other ones like email, name equals email, that basically does validation that says it's got to have an @ sign, there's some rules about what is and isn't a valid email.

00:09:51.040 --> 00:09:57.120
 And so this will refuse to submit this form unless there's a valid email in there.

00:09:57.120 --> 00:10:10.720
 The same is true for number, if you put something that's like 25 and it's not between one and five with min and max here, if we're going to refuse to submit the form, the same is true for a type equals URL.

00:10:10.720 --> 00:10:30.240
 There's really a validation on the form to say, look, you can't put something in here that's not a valid URL and just to prove that it doesn't matter, if you make any type, which flying doesn't exist, you can type something in and it just functions as a text field and so in a way all these fall back to text fields.

00:10:30.240 --> 00:10:57.280
 The key thing is, is when you hit the submit button, normally that gathers up the form and sends it to the server, but when you use this HTML5 validation like date, number, email, URL, it actually will, before it, before it, you hit the submit button, before it actually sends it, it's going to do a quick validation on these things and it will actually stop and say, you know what, you didn't get that one right and it just refuses to submit.

00:10:57.280 --> 00:11:06.320
 You can't override that in your application. What happens is, is the data doesn't get submitted at all until, so the browser blocks the submission of the data.

00:11:06.320 --> 00:11:27.200
 Now, if it's not an HTML5 browser, it's going to get submitted with no validation whatsoever, so we still have to kind of check this data for sanity, which we'll talk about soon about how to do that in the server, but this is quite nice because it gives your user some immediate feedback, kind of customized to the browser so the browser takes some responsibility for helping get the user to type the right stuff in.

00:11:28.240 --> 00:11:38.240
 And so that is a romp through HTML forms. You will learn so much more. I just wanted to kind of cover some of them in case you hadn't seen it in a while.

